/* Entering a Maxima break point. Type 'exit;' to resume. */
/* _ipar:[1,4,5,3,8000,500,1,0,1,0,0]$ */
/* [1, 4, 5, 3, 8000, 500, 1, 0, 1, 0, 0] */
/* _tol:[1d-6,1d-6,1d-6]$ */
/* [1.0e-6, 1.0e-6, 1.0e-6] */
/* _exit; */
/*  e =  6.499999997869993   that is n+1/2 with n=6 */
/* (%o1)                              osc2.mac */
/* A perfect plot appears. */
/* (%i2) time(%); */
/* (%o2)                             [0.679482] */

/* Problem: why is the correct result so sensible to ipar, and to what ? */
/* setting the number of collocation points ipar[2] to 4 is not sufficient. */
/* The computation converges much slower to the solution for n=8 instead of 6 */
/* Setting ipar:[1, 2, 10, 3, 40000, 2500, -1, 0, 1, 0, 0] works OK. */
/* Setting both ipar[2]:4 and ipar[3]:10 works very well and fast. Strangely */
/* with the standard ipar  [1, 2, 5, 3 ..] but the guess p=(1.0-x^4)*exp(-x^2/2) */
/* the solution is fine with n=6. If one changes the guess to */
/*  p=(1.0+4.0*x^4)*exp(-x^2/2) one obtains the solution for n=30! Recall: */
/* hermite(6,x) = -(120*(-((8*x^6)/15)+4*x^4-6*x^2+1)) */
/* Amusingly one can take the guess p=cos(%pi*x/4) and obtain the correct */
/* solution, for n=6. With other values of the angle, different values of */
/* n appear. */

